{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":31393,"record_hash":"sha256:b146aa46636a4ace5a79ecc860d0c0460fb3b36b9d928512070964491a8a210b","timestamp":"2026-05-11T17:33:10.061Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"assistant","text":"Yeah, that’s exactly where it ended up, and I think that’s the right split.\n\n`but-agentlog` now mostly does product-specific things:\n\n- defines the agentlog key scope\n- exposes `but agentlog sync`\n- defaults `--remote` to `origin`\n- keeps output simple\n\nGitMeta owns the lifecycle mechanics:\n\n- scoped serialization\n- scoped materialization\n- scoped fetch/push refs\n- retry after non-fast-forward\n- preserving unrelated metadata\n- merging set/list values correctly\n\nThat feels appropriate because `agentlog sync` is not really special transport. It is “sync this named slice of metadata.” If we had implemented that in `but-agentlog`, we would have duplicated GitMeta semantics outside GitMeta and probably created a second, less reliable sync engine.\n\nThe important thing is that GitMeta did not get a GitButler-specific API. The new concept is general: `SyncScope`. Agentlog is just the first concrete caller.\n\nThe only thing to keep an eye on is API weight. We added a real public surface in GitMeta, so before publishing I’d still do one more quick scan for “is this API the smallest honest version?” But directionally, yes: the implementation being mostly in GitMeta is a feature, not an accident.","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-11T17:33:10.061Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"assistant","phase":"final_answer"}}}